          "body": "Exodus 27 opens with the bronze altar (27:1-8), and this is not accidental. In the tabernacle's spatial theology, the altar is the first sacred object a worshiper encounters after entering the court gate. Before bread (the table of showbread, ch. 25), before light (the lampstand, ch. 25), before the presence (the ark, ch. 25) — there is blood and fire. The altar's dimensions (5×5×3 cubits), its acacia-wood frame overlaid with bronze, its four horns, its grating, its carrying poles — each detail enforces the same theological point: approach to the holy God is sacrificial or it is nothing. The horns (*qeren*, 27:2) deserve particular attention. They are 'of one piece with it' — integral, inseparable from the altar's structure. The horns served multiple functions: blood was applied to them (29:12), and they provided asylum for those who clung to them (1 Kings 1:50-51; 2:28). Mercy and judgment are architecturally fused at the altar's four corners. There is no version of this structure without the horns."
