          "body": "Verse 8 is the altar section's theological hinge: 'as it was shown to you in the mountain, so they shall make it.' The altar is hollow — built of planks, not solid material (27:8). Commentators (following the Mishnah, Middoth 3:1) suggest that in the wilderness the hollow frame was filled with earth or stones at each encampment, recalling the earlier altar-law of Exodus 20:24-25 where God commanded an earthen altar. The hollow construction also facilitates transport — the same portable theology expressed in the carrying poles (27:6-7). But the verse's theological weight falls on the mountain pattern. The earthly altar does not originate in human liturgical creativity; it mirrors a heavenly archetype shown to Moses at Sinai. The author of Hebrews will make this explicit: Moses was told 'See that you make all things according to the pattern which was shown you on the mountain' (Hebrews 8:5, citing Exodus 25:40, applicable throughout the tabernacle instructions). Every cubit of the altar is a cubit of divine revelation. The precision of the specification is itself theological: God cares about the structure through which sinners approach Him."
