          "body": "The court specification (27:9-19) is the most architecturally elaborate section of the chapter. One hundred cubits on the long sides (north and south), fifty cubits on the short sides (east and west) — an enclosure roughly the size of half a football field. The perimeter is defined by fine twisted linen hangings (*shesh shazar*, 27:9, 18) — the same linen used for the innermost tabernacle curtains (26:1). Purity is not reserved for the inner sanctuary alone; the court boundary itself is woven from priestly linen. The posts carry a material theology: their bases are bronze (grounding the court in the material of judgment) while their hooks and bands are silver (the metal of ransom, anticipating the half-shekel redemption of Exodus 30:11-16). The gate (27:16) is the chapter's single most significant architectural element. Twenty cubits wide — wider than the tabernacle entrance (26:36 was also twenty cubits) — it faces east and is woven in blue, purple, scarlet, and fine linen. Its four colors match every inner sanctuary screen (26:31, 36; 27:16; 28:5). The architectural message is deliberate: the gate already belongs to the same holy vocabulary as the veil before the Most Holy Place. To cross this threshold is to begin the ascent into the divine presence. And there is only one such gate."
