          "body": "No chapter of Exodus 25–31 stands alone; each is a brick in the architectural argument that culminates in the glory filling the tabernacle (40:34-35). Exodus 27 specifically contributes the theology of mediated access. Every element of the chapter resists unmediated approach: the altar requires sacrifice before God is approached; the court requires passage through a single gate; the lamp requires priestly maintenance; the statute requires generational continuity. The New Testament's engagement with this architecture is extensive. Hebrews 9:1-10 surveys the tabernacle's 'regulations of divine worship' and concludes they were 'a symbol for the present time' — a shadow of the better things secured by Christ's high-priestly ministry (Hebrews 10:1). The bronze altar of Exodus 27 finds its fulfillment in the cross, where the Son of God absorbed the fire of divine judgment so that worshipers might pass through — not the gate of a linen court, but the 'new and living way through the veil, that is, His flesh' (Hebrews 10:20). John 10:9 makes explicit what the court's single gate implies: 'I am the door; if anyone enters through Me, he will be saved.' The perpetual lamp of 27:20-21 finds its eschatological climax in Revelation 21:23, where 'the city has no need of the sun or of the moon to shine on it, for the glory of God has illumined it, and its lamp is the Lamb.' The shadow is real; the substance it points to is Christ."
